==Abstract==

This IIP describes Erlay, a transaction relay protocol using set reconciliation to reduce bandwidth. It is adapted from BIP 330 for INTcoin.

==Motivation==

Traditional transaction relay floods the network: each transaction is announced to all peers. With 8 connections, each transaction is announced ~8 times. Erlay reduces this to ~1.5 times on average, saving ~40% of transaction relay bandwidth.

==Specification==

===Protocol Overview===

# Nodes exchange transaction announcements via reconciliation instead of flooding
# Periodically, peers reconcile their transaction sets using Minisketch
# Only the differences are transmitted

===Messages===

'''sendtxrcncl''': Signal reconciliation support
<pre>
version:  uint32  // Protocol version
salt:     uint64  // Per-connection salt
</pre>

'''reqtxrcncl''': Request reconciliation
<pre>
(empty)
</pre>

'''sketch''': Set sketch for reconciliation
<pre>
sketch_data: []byte  // Minisketch-encoded set
</pre>

'''reqsketchext''': Request sketch extension
<pre>
short_ids: []uint32  // Short IDs needing full wtxids
</pre>

===Reconciliation Algorithm===

# Alice and Bob each maintain a reconciliation set
# When reconciling, Alice sends her sketch
# Bob computes the symmetric difference
# Bob requests any transactions he's missing

===Short ID Calculation===

<pre>
short_id = SipHash(salt_alice || salt_bob, wtxid) & 0xffffffff
</pre>

===Fallback===

If reconciliation fails (too many differences), nodes fall back to traditional inv flooding for that round.

==Rationale==

===Why Minisketch?===

Minisketch enables efficient set reconciliation:
* O(d) communication where d is set difference
* Works without knowing which elements differ
* BCH code-based, well-understood mathematically

